I’m in her cheering section, in her corner and have her back. Eboni Major, the first African American Whiskey Blender, released her first whiskey since her departure from Diageo’s controversial *problematic* Bulleit Brand (she blended for a large number of the corporation’s brands, but only got publicly accredited with one, an unfortunate but common occurrence whithin spirit giants). Her love letter to her hometown Birmingham, was blended from Bourbons produced by @dreadriverco, located very near to where one of the most important and influential women in her life, her grandmother, had lived. It was so special to see her shining and the distillery packed with people excited about her creation and there to celebrate her achievement. Not to mention experience the talents of Tiffanie Barriere @thedrinkingcoach and Josh Davis @mrmixologist There is so much ahead for you @majorinwhiskey l am so grateful for the chance to change the world together. Here’s to the grace and excellence of this woman, and history being made right before our eyes.

Today, I finally get to share with you one of the most important steps in my career as a Master Distiller: releasing my own product that I created from start to finish. With our first small batch release of Forbidden Bourbon, I have the opportunity to really show you what I’m capable of and I couldn’t be more proud of my teammates for this product. To have been forbidden as a female Master Distiller legally up until the mid 70s when the laws were repealed, it feels amazing to be able to make my mark in Kentucky Bourbon. Today we announce the official launch of Forbidden Bourbon, a bold and elegant recipe of white corn and white wheat with a high percentage of barley made to honor the Southern roots of our founders, my culinary perspective, and using food-grade grain versus feed-grade grain make all the difference in the experience you will have with Forbidden. Our pre-order link is live and I hope that you will give it a try :-) Sometimes when you go against the grain, in the face of what is forbidden, you can come out on the other side with something really special. DrinkForbidden.com

The word forbidden, much like a song, means many things to different people. When nothing is Forbidden, perfection is possible. The bottle may look a little sharp and scary (Forbidden you might say), but get one of the in your hand it nothing feels better. A few observers have noticed the Single Barrel version of our label in these images. It’s coming! Cask strength single barrels will be live when everything hits the shelf in June (KY, TN, GA & SC)! #drinkforbidden @forbiddenbourbon

We had our debut event to celebrate the launch of Forbidden last night and pictures will only barely give a tiny peek into the magic. I am so grateful for the friendship and support of @gardenandgun they are impeccable hosts. What a memorable way to honor the southern roots of our brand and it’s owners. I’m going to try to make sure this doesn’t sound like an acceptance speech, but there are way too many people to acknowledge and thank for being a part of this dream and bringing it to life. We’re finally at the starting line of the marathon and I think we’ve got the stuff to take us the distance! #drinkforbidden @cameronwilder @dean.renaud @valpascoe (aka the wizard of forbidden)
If you’re interested in trying and not located in TN, KY, GA or SC the pre sale link is your chance for a limited time - drinkforbidden.com (in bio)

Juneteenth marks the date when all enslaved black humans were finally free. This day, in 1865, comes two years after the emancipation proclamation upon dismantling the last southern slavery strongholds in Texas, and marks the first step to our country truly fulfilling the promises it made in the constitution that all men are indeed equal. Please take some time today to learn more about how far we still have to go. Specifically, the Master Class on Back History, Black Freedom and Black Love is a great start. Happy Freedom Day my friends ❤️💛💚

Just being at the table has been enough to cause vitriol. Although, I have never felt out of place in a group of men. From auto shop in high school to pursuing engineering professionally, I always just focused on doing what I love to my highest ability. As it turns out I’m not only capable, but excellent. So all of you who questioned “the hype” you can respectfully go kick rocks. I’m competing only with myself, and my intention is to make this industry completely unrecognizable to the old white male establishment. If you’re offended, you’re an impediment, but I’m not worried. Because there are so many more of us that are leading this industry to higher heights, and the only way we will get there is to broaden it in every single possible way. Here’s to the ones who boldly trespass in Forbidden spaces, we hold the keys to the future. (Photo 1 - Kentucky Bourbon Festival 2014, Photo 2 - Master Distillers Panel Bourbon Classic 2016)

It had been a little bit since I did the full single barrel experience with a group. So grateful to our production partners @bardstownbourbonco for helping create a memorable day for these folks who were lucky enough to win a barrel from a charity auction. They got kind of stuck because different folks in the group loved all 4 of their options, but they finally agreed on one and plan to age it a few more years! (Although it was super delicious right now also!!) The reason it says Castle & Key on the barrel is because this is a 5 year old barrel that I made while I was still Master Distiller there. And it has been aging since then here at Bardstown Bourbon Company in their new beautiful Rickhouses. This barrel is 115 proof (due to our lower entry proof) and we’ll see if that increases more over time (it *usually* does) CHEERS!

This is my senior portrait. I’m in my Taco Bell uniform probably leaving from my shift. My senior year had some serious highs and lows. I’m sure there’s somebody out there that has my high school yearbook that could show you the photos that the school took, but I didn’t get professional photos taken. I was not the girl that people expected great things from. I was quiet and shy, and underperformed intentionally to stay invisible. Maybe it’s the middle child syndrome or maybe it’s my introverted personality. I’m so grateful to her for not just doing what anyone expected, perhaps without knowing it, she paved the way for courage and confidence to grow. #lookatusnow

🥃Exciting update!🥃

Over the last few months, @sxsw sorted through thousands of session proposals via #PanelPicker entries (up 33% compared to last season). And we're thrilled to share that our panel was selected! 

All four of us are extremely passionate about whiskey. While the industry has made progress in the spirit's innovation, there's still much to be discussed and done to improve representation and inclusion in the whiskey space. In fact, in a recent survey conducted by @ourwhisky_foundation, 67% of respondents said whiskey's masculine representation makes their jobs more challenging.

So, in this discussion we will highlight the spirit of women in whiskey and highlight ways the industry can proactively do better. 

See you all in March at #sxsw2024!
